<HEADLINE>
<P>
FULLERTON VOTERS WANT AN ELECTION, AND THEY'LL GET IT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * Recent editorials, letters to the editor and news reports regarding the 
controversy surrounding the forthcoming Fullerton council election may have 
created a misperception in some minds. Current published accounts appear to 
imply that voters in the June 7 recall election called for a special election 
as opposed to electing recalled council member replacements during the next 
general election. 
</P>
<P>
 The fact is our ballot choice was between a special election and replacement 
by appointment, should the recall prevail. Thus, the majority of voters opted 
to have recalled council members replaced by the election process rather than 
by appointment by the remaining two council members. 
</P>
<P>
 Because of the ballot options given, I voted for replacement by election. 
However, if the ballot choice had been between a special election and the 
general election, and had related costs been accurately established and 
effectively communicated to the voting public, I would have opted for the Nov. 
8 general election. I believe a large number of Fullerton voters would have 
done the same if for no other reason than to save the estimated expense of a 
special election. 
</P>
<P>
 E.M. GINTER 
</P>
<P>
 Fullerton 
</P>
<P>
 * Enough of this self-serving blathering about "honor" among the three 
recalled Fullerton City Council members (Hal McDonnel, Letters, July 17). 
</P>
<P>
 He thinks they should resign at once -- which would create difficult legal 
problems that might not be sorted out for ages. In any case, he wants the 
special election to fill the three seats held as early as possible, not 
consolidated with the November general election. 
</P>
<P>
 If Mr. McDonnel is interested in honor, why doesn't he mention that the 
earliest possible date for a special election would be Oct. 18 -- barely three 
weeks before the general election at which time this matter will be settled. 
</P>
<P>
 It is the height of foolishness to have an election whose outcome might be 
reversed only three weeks later. 
</P>
<P>
 BARBARA KENT 
</P>
<P>
 Fullerton 
</P>
</TEXT>
