<HEADLINE>
<P>
BASEBALL / DAILY REPORT; AROUND THE MAJORS; DYKSTRA, HOLLINS BACK -- FOR A 
WHILE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Philadelphia Phillies activated Lenny Dykstra and Dave Hollins from the 
disabled list and optioned pitchers Andy Carter and Paul Quantrill to triple-A 
Scranton-Wilkes-Barre. 
</P>
<P>
 Dykstra and Hollins were in the lineup for Saturday night's game against the 
San Diego Padres, Dykstra in center field and Hollins in right. 
</P>
<P>
 Hollins, normally a third baseman, left the game in the seventh inning 
complaining of pain in his left hand. He will have X-rays today to confirm 
whether he had fractured the hamate bone in his left hand. 
</P>
<P>
 Earlier this season Hollins broke another bone in the same hand, but last year 
broke the hamate bone in his right hand. 
</P>
<P>
 "My hand was getting a little tired as the game went on," Hollins said. "In my 
third at-bat I felt something like a break in my hand. It's just a nightmarish 
season for me." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The Minnesota Twins activated right-hander Pat Mahomes and designated hitter 
Dave Winfield from the disabled list. . . . Reliever Gene Harris, who had been 
pitching for the Tigers' triple-A affiliate in Toledo on a rehabilitation 
assignment, was activated from the disabled list. The Tigers placed pitcher 
Greg Gohr on the 15-day disabled list, retroactive to July 20. 
</P>
